entry.title: Include client hints in prefetch requests
entry.content:
Client hints headers are appropriate to send in prefetch requests,

at least those for origins where client hints and cookies are sent

for subresource and scripted fetches.



In the cross-site case, this is currently limited to "low-entropy"

client hints which are always sent, but a feature param to allow

changing this if an unanticipated issue comes up is included

nonetheless.



This feature is disabled by default in this CL; a followup CL will

change this to enabled by default (and that CL can be cleanly

reverted alone if necessary without totally unwinding this one).

related to the application lifetime). Use the `ios_is_app_extension`

based on API not available to application extension).

building application extensions (which allow catching API that is not

available to application extensions).

entry.title: Share Cronet telemetry code between API and impl
entry.content:
IMPORTANT: this CL has breaking implications for downstream Cronet

release channels and requires dependency structure adjustments for

consumers (e.g. internal Google repo, Maven). The new "shared" JAR will

need to be shipped to consumers as a dependency of *both* API and impl

JARs.



This CL introduces a new Cronet distribution JAR,

"cronet_shared_java.jar", which holds code that is shared between all

Cronet code, i.e. the API *and* implementations. Such code is reusable

from anywhere inside the Cronet codebase.



The main distinction between "API" code and "shared" code is that

implementations do not necessarily ship with the API code. The textbook

example of that is the Cronet impl in Google Play Services, which uses

the API classes from the calling app instead of having its own copy.

In contrast, implementations always ship with shared code, such that if

the API code and impl code are loaded from different sources (which

implies potentially different build/version), each side will end up with

its own private copy of the shared classes, thus sidestepping any ABI

compatibility concerns. The downside is that references to these classes

can't cross the Cronet API/impl ABI boundary, but that's fine for what

we want to use this for.

entry.title: Reland "[HitTestOpaqueness] Record hit test data for scrolling backgrounds"
entry.content:
This reverts commit a3b577901f678c9ae60eca39c01d5b5e5faffeb2.



Rebaseline the form control text area test on Fuchsia.



Original change's description:

> Revert "[HitTestOpaqueness] Record hit test data for scrolling backgrounds"

>

> This reverts commit 207bf7b49ef751a431403cd5b3d331b906a53712.

>

> Reason for revert:

> LUCI Bisection has identified this change as the cause of a test failure. See the analysis: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/bisection/test-analysis/b/5192936604041216

>

> Sample build with failed test: https://ci.chromium.org/b/8756253222175672209

> Affected test(s):

> [ninja://content/test:content_browsertests/FormControlsBrowserTest.Textarea](https://ci.chromium.org/ui/test/chromium/ninja:%2F%2Fcontent%2Ftest:content_browsertests%2FFormControlsBrowserTest.Textarea?q=VHash%3A2d14ec82adda2392)

>

> If this is a false positive, please report it at http://b.corp.google.com/createIssue?component=1199205&description=Analysis%3A+https%3A%2F%2Fci.chromium.org%2Fui%2Fp%2Fchromium%2Fbisection%2Ftest-analysis%2Fb%2F5192936604041216&format=PLAIN&priority=P3&title=Wrongly+blamed+https%3A%2F%2Fchromium-review.googlesource.com%2Fc%2Fchromium%2Fsrc%2F%2B%2F5278235&type=BUG

>

> Original change's description:

> > [HitTestOpaqueness] Record hit test data for scrolling backgrounds

> >

> > This doesn't help much to HitTestOpaqueness itself because the visible

> > area of scrolling contents is also covered by the ScrollHitTestData of

> > the scroller which ensures opaqueness to hit test if the scroller is

> > opaque to hit test.

> >

> > The actual benefits are:

> > - This may improve scroll performance for scrolling contents that

> > don't have a background. The new hit test data will make most

> > scrolling contents layers to be always the same size as the

> > scroll overflow regardless of the cull rect (which may change on

> > scroll), to avoid full layer rerasterization when the cull rect

> > change affects the bounds of the painted scrolling contents.

> > - This may help crbug.com/324285520 because the new hit test data

> > carries special hit test data.

> > - This also prepares for a CL for UseRecordedBoundsForTiling to

> > prevent extra rasterization (caused by change of the origin of the

> > tiling rect) during scroll.

> >

entry.title: Revert "[HitTestOpaqueness] Record hit test data for scrolling backgrounds"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 207bf7b49ef751a431403cd5b3d331b906a53712.



Reason for revert:

LUCI Bisection has identified this change as the cause of a test failure. See the analysis: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/bisection/test-analysis/b/5192936604041216



Sample build with failed test: https://ci.chromium.org/b/8756253222175672209

Affected test(s):

[ninja://content/test:content_browsertests/FormControlsBrowserTest.Textarea](https://ci.chromium.org/ui/test/chromium/ninja:%2F%2Fcontent%2Ftest:content_browsertests%2FFormControlsBrowserTest.Textarea?q=VHash%3A2d14ec82adda2392)



If this is a false positive, please report it at http://b.corp.google.com/createIssue?component=1199205&description=Analysis%3A+https%3A%2F%2Fci.chromium.org%2Fui%2Fp%2Fchromium%2Fbisection%2Ftest-analysis%2Fb%2F5192936604041216&format=PLAIN&priority=P3&title=Wrongly+blamed+https%3A%2F%2Fchromium-review.googlesource.com%2Fc%2Fchromium%2Fsrc%2F%2B%2F5278235&type=BUG



Original change's description:

> [HitTestOpaqueness] Record hit test data for scrolling backgrounds

>

> This doesn't help much to HitTestOpaqueness itself because the visible

> area of scrolling contents is also covered by the ScrollHitTestData of

> the scroller which ensures opaqueness to hit test if the scroller is

> opaque to hit test.

>

> The actual benefits are:

> - This may improve scroll performance for scrolling contents that

> don't have a background. The new hit test data will make most

> scrolling contents layers to be always the same size as the

> scroll overflow regardless of the cull rect (which may change on

Some UKMs are tied to notification events, which have

a separate lifecycle from page visits. This means the

new SourceId type, which is not subject to the same

history visit count requirement.



The expected impact of this change is a recovery of 30%

of revocation UKMs and 38% of notification usage events

that are dropped due to the background recorder

requirements.

entry.title: [Extensions] Fix memory leak in ExtensionHost.
entry.content:
Before this change, we would add event messages for lazy and non-lazy

background pages to unacked_messages_ of ExtensionHost. However, we

didn't remove those messages on browser event ack in all cases which can

leak memory. For events that use the

EventRouter::DispatchEventToSender() event flow (mostly webRequest API

events from persistent background pages), we would not remove the event

message from unacked_messages_ and it would persist until restart. This

is because we only remove the message for lazy background pages.



After this change, like EventRouter::DispatchEventToProcess(), we now

remove the event message from unacked_messages_ on browser event ack for

all background pages to close this leak.



Also added tests to ensure unacked_messages_ is cleared for

EventRouter::DispatchEventToProcess() for both background page types and

for EventRouter::DispatchEventToSender() for just persistent background

pages (event pages can't use the webRequest API).
